{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646893"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:38:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:38:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18216"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18216"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.14,0.1,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10930"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79352"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10930"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18216"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64674"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"10200"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25411"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79352"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBone formation requires the coordinated activity of several specialised cell types. The mineralisation of bone tissue is a crucial process that provides structural integrity to the skeleton.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cell types is primarily responsible for producing hydroxyapatite crystals in bone tissue?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Osteoblasts","Osteoclasts","Osteocytes","Chondrocytes","Fibroblasts"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoblasts\u003C/strong\u003E are specialised bone-forming cells responsible for synthesising and secreting the organic bone matrix components and regulating the deposition of hydroxyapatite crystals. These cells coordinate the mineralisation process that gives bone its characteristic strength and rigidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoclasts\u003C/strong\u003E are multinucleated cells that break down and resorb bone tissue through the secretion of acids and enzymes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteocytes\u003C/strong\u003E are mature bone cells embedded within the mineralised matrix that maintain bone tissue and regulate mineral homeostasis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChondrocytes\u003C/strong\u003E are specialised cells found in cartilage that produce and maintain cartilaginous matrix\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibroblasts\u003C/strong\u003E are connective tissue cells that produce collagen and other extracellular matrix components but are not involved in bone mineralisation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe coordinated activities of these different cell types maintain proper bone structure and function throughout life.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Osteoblasts synthesise and secrete bone matrix proteins and regulate the mineralisation process in bone formation.","Hydroxyapatite crystals provide structural strength to bone tissue through their incorporation into the organic matrix.","Different bone cells have distinct roles: osteoblasts form bone, osteoclasts resorb bone, and osteocytes maintain bone."],"references":["Khurana, I., Khurana, A., \u0026 Kowlgi, N. G. (2019). Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clarke B. Normal bone anatomy and physiology. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2008 Nov;3 Suppl 3(Suppl 3):S131-9. doi: 10.2215/CJN.04151206. PMID: 18988698; PMCID: PMC3152283","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746. doi: 10.1155/2015/421746. Epub 2015 Jul 13. PMID: 26247020; PMCID: PMC4515490","Cowan PT, Launico MV, Kahai P. Anatomy, Bones. 2024 Apr 21. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725884"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64674"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18216"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64674"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T10:21:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T10:28:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10930"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79352"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and ret